="false" data-tooltip-state="closed"><div style="opacity: 1;"><svg viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="size-5"><path d="M8 2C6.89543 2 6 2.89543 6 4V14C6 15.1046 6.89543 16 8 16H14C15.1046 16 16 15.1046 16 14V4C16 2.89543 15.1046 2 14 2H8ZM7 4C7 3.44772 7.44772 3 8 3H14C14.5523 3 15 3.44772 15 4V14C15 14.5523 14.5523 15 14 15H8C7.44772 15 7 14.5523 7 14V4ZM4 6.00001C4 5.25973 4.4022 4.61339 5 4.26758V14.5C5 15.8807 6.11929 17 7.5 17H13.7324C13.3866 17.5978 12.7403 18 12 18H7.5C5.567 18 4 16.433 4 14.5V6.00001Z"></path></svg></div></button></div></div><div class="font-ligatures-none relative h-fit max-w-user-text-message whitespace-pre-wrap break-words px-4 py-2.5 squircle-16 bg-accent-250/60 dark:bg-accent-200 text-base self-end" data-content="user-message">When sorting, if an item can be in more than one list, should also be included in each list. So, using the example of steam, we would find it in the list under atmosphere and in the list under hydrosphere, then straights listed under hydrosphere and geosphere. Or if we use these spheres as tags it would be steam (atmosphere, hydrosphere), and straights (geosphere, hydrosphere)</div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-tabster="{&quot;groupper&quot;:{&quot;tabbability&quot;:2},&quot;focusable&quot;:{}}" class="group/ai-message" data-content="ai-message" data-testid="ai-message" aria-labelledby="huW7M9Mab91EbUWY33Fum-author huW7M9Mab91EbUWY33Fum-content-0" tabindex="0" role="article"><div class="relative"><h6 id="huW7M9Mab91EbUWY33Fum-author" class="sr-only" aria-label="Copilot said" data-copy="false">Copilot said</h6></div><div class="space-y-3 mt-3"><div class="group/ai-message-item space-y-3 break-words" id="huW7M9Mab91EbUWY33Fum-content-0"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Using the spheres as <strong>tags</strong> rather than exclusive buckets is the right mental model. When an item naturally belongs to more than one sphere, it should appear in <em>each</em> relevant list, or be written with tags like:</span></p><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>steam (Atmosphere, Hydrosphere)</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>straits (Geosphere, Hydrosphere)</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>peat bogs (Biosphere, Geosphere, Hydrosphere)</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>urban wetlands (Anthrosphere, Hydrosphere, Biosphere)</strong></span></p></li></ul><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">This creates a system that behaves more like an ecological ontology than a rigid taxonomy.</span></p><div class="relative pb-6 w-full after:border-b after:border-stroke-300 after:w-full after:absolute after:mt-3"></div><h2 class="text-xl-medium [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5 pb-1">How multi‑sphere classification works</h2><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Each sphere represents a <strong>dimension</strong> of the environment. An item can intersect multiple dimensions depending on:</span></p><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">its physical state</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">the processes that create or maintain it</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">the systems it interacts with</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">the context in which you’re using it</span></p></li></ul><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">This lets you classify complex or hybrid features without forcing them into a single category.</span></p><h3 class="text-lg-strong pb-1 [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5">Examples of natural overlaps</h3><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>Fog</strong> → Atmosphere + Hydrosphere</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>Permafrost</strong> → Geosphere + Hydrosphere (cryosphere)</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>Mangroves</strong> → Biosphere + Hydrosphere + Geosphere</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>Irrigated farmland</strong> → Anthrosphere + Hydrosphere + Biosphere</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>Volcanic ash clouds</strong> → Geosphere + Atmosphere</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>Coral reefs</strong> → Biosphere + Hydrosphere + Geosphere</span></p></li></ul><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">This mirrors how Earth‑system science treats environmental components: as interacting spheres rather than isolated domains.</span></p><div class="relative pb-6 w-full after:border-b after:border-stroke-300 after:w-full after:absolute after:mt-3"></div><h2 class="text-xl-medium [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5 pb-1">Applying this to your earlier list</h2><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Here are a few items from your list rewritten in the tag format you described:</span></p><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>arctic zones (Atmosphere, Geosphere, Hydrosphere)</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>constructed waterways (Anthrosphere, Hydrosphere)</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>erosion (Geosphere, Hydrosphere, Atmosphere)</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>extremophiles (Biosphere, Geosphere, Hydrosphere)</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>abandoned settlements (Anthrosphere, Geosphere)</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>glacial zones (Hydrosphere, Geosphere, Atmosphere)</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>high biodiversity (Biosphere)</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>crystal laced (Geosphere)</strong> unless magical, then (Other)</span></p></li></ul><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">If you want, I can convert your entire list into this tag‑style format.</span></p><div class="relative pb-6 w-full after:border-b after:border-stroke-300 after:w-full after:absolute after:mt-3"></div><h2 class="text-xl-medium [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5 pb-1">Why this approach scales well</h2><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">It avoids forcing ambiguous items into a single “best” category.</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">It captures the real complexity of environmental systems.</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">It works for scientific, fictional, and game‑design contexts.</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">It allows filtering by sphere (e.g., “show me all Hydrosphere items”).</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">It supports future expansion without breaking the structure.</span></p></li></ul><div class="relative pb-6 w-full after:border-b after:border-stroke-300 after:w-full after:absolute after:mt-3"></div><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">If you’d like, I can now take your full list and produce a clean, multi‑sphere tagged version that matches this system.</span></p></div></div><div class="mt-3"><div class="flex opacity-0 transition-opacity duration-300 ease-in-out items-center group-focus-within/ai-message-item:opacity-100 group-hover/ai-message-item:opacity-100 group-focus-within/ai-message:opacity-100 group-hover/ai-message:opacity-100" data-copy="false" data-testid="message-item-reactions"><button aria-label="Good response" aria-pressed="false" type="button" class="relative flex items-center text-foreground-800 fill-foreground-800 active:text-foreground-600 active:fill-foreground-600 dark:active:text-foreground-650 dark:active:fill-foreground-650 bg-transparent safe-hover:bg-black/5 active:bg-black/3 dark:safe-hover:bg-white/8 dark:active:bg-white/5 text-sm justify-center size-9