><div class="relative space-y-3"><h5 class="sr-only" aria-label="You said" data-copy="false">You said</h5><div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1"><div class="flex w-full items-start"><div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1"><div class="flex gap-2 justify-end"><div role="group" class="relative z-10 flex opacity-0 transition-opacity duration-300 ease-in-out group-focus-within/user-message:opacity-100 group-hover/user-message:opacity-100 items-center mt-auto" data-copy="false" data-testid="user-message-reactions"><div class="relative"><button aria-label="Copy message" type="button" class="relative flex items-center text-foreground-800 fill-foreground-800 active:text-foreground-600 active:fill-foreground-600 dark:active:text-foreground-650 dark:active:fill-foreground-650 bg-transparent safe-hover:bg-black/5 active:bg-black/3 dark:safe-hover:bg-white/8 dark:active:bg-white/5 text-sm justify-center size-9 rounded-xl after:rounded-xl after:absolute after:inset-0 after:pointer-events-none after:border after:border-transparent after:contrast-more:border-2 outline-2 outline-offset-1 focus-visible:z-[1] focus-visible:outline focus-visible:outline-stroke-900" data-testid="copy-user-message-button" data-spatial-navigation-autofocus="false" data-tooltip-state="closed"><div style="opacity: 1;"><svg viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="size-5"><path d="M8 2C6.89543 2 6 2.89543 6 4V14C6 15.1046 6.89543 16 8 16H14C15.1046 16 16 15.1046 16 14V4C16 2.89543 15.1046 2 14 2H8ZM7 4C7 3.44772 7.44772 3 8 3H14C14.5523 3 15 3.44772 15 4V14C15 14.5523 14.5523 15 14 15H8C7.44772 15 7 14.5523 7 14V4ZM4 6.00001C4 5.25973 4.4022 4.61339 5 4.26758V14.5C5 15.8807 6.11929 17 7.5 17H13.7324C13.3866 17.5978 12.7403 18 12 18H7.5C5.567 18 4 16.433 4 14.5V6.00001Z"></path></svg></div></button></div></div><div class="font-ligatures-none relative h-fit max-w-user-text-message whitespace-pre-wrap break-words px-4 py-2.5 squircle-16 bg-accent-250/60 dark:bg-accent-200 text-base self-end" data-content="user-message">Let's add into these rules that if there is something similar like snow cap and snow caps we'll go with the plural of snow caps. If we have something like frost covered and frost-covered which should we use, and we'll need to make it uniform</div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-tabster="{&quot;groupper&quot;:{&quot;tabbability&quot;:2},&quot;focusable&quot;:{}}" class="group/ai-message" data-content="ai-message" data-testid="ai-message" aria-labelledby="yF1qZ7zA3dpGTtUYwZwWS-author yF1qZ7zA3dpGTtUYwZwWS-content-0" tabindex="0" role="article"><div class="relative"><h6 id="yF1qZ7zA3dpGTtUYwZwWS-author" class="sr-only" aria-label="Copilot said" data-copy="false">Copilot said</h6></div><div class="space-y-3 mt-3"><div class="group/ai-message-item space-y-3 break-words" id="yF1qZ7zA3dpGTtUYwZwWS-content-0"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">A clean naming‑convention rule will make your entire system easier to maintain, search, and audit. Here’s the version that fits naturally with the way you’ve been organizing everything so far.</span></p><div class="relative pb-6 w-full after:border-b after:border-stroke-300 after:w-full after:absolute after:mt-3"></div><h2 class="text-xl-medium [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5 pb-1">🌍 Core Naming‑Convention Rules</h2><h3 class="text-lg-strong pb-1 [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5"><strong>1. Always choose the </strong><em><strong>plural</strong></em><strong> form when both singular and plural exist</strong></h3><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">This keeps the list consistent and avoids duplicates.</span></p><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Examples:</span></p><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>snow caps</strong> instead of <em>snow cap</em></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>grasslands</strong> instead of <em>grassland</em></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>frost heaves</strong> instead of <em>frost heave</em></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>bog pools</strong> instead of <em>bog pool</em></span></p></li></ul><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Plural is the default unless the concept is inherently singular (e.g., “bedrock,” “permafrost,” “tundra”).</span></p><div class="relative pb-6 w-full after:border-b after:border-stroke-300 after:w-full after:absolute after:mt-3"></div><h3 class="text-lg-strong pb-1 [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5"><strong>2. For hyphenated vs. spaced forms, choose the version that is:</strong></h3><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>most standard in environmental science</strong>,</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>most readable</strong>,</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>least ambiguous</strong>,</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>and consistent across similar terms</strong>.</span></p></li></ul><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">This gives us:</span></p><h4 class="text-md-strong"><strong>Use hyphens when the phrase is a compound adjective modifying a noun</strong></h4><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Examples:</span></p><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>frost‑covered terrain</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>snow‑covered peaks</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>wind‑shaped dunes</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>fire‑adapted species</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>cold‑region landscapes</strong></span></p></li></ul><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Hyphens make it clear that the words function together as a single descriptor.</span></p><h4 class="text-md-strong"><strong>Use spaces when the phrase is a noun phrase, not a compound modifier</strong></h4><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Examples:</span></p><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>frost covered</strong> (if used as a standalone descriptor, not modifying a noun)</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>snow caps</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>grass fires</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>ice fields</strong></span></p></li></ul><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">But in your list, almost all of these appear as <strong>modifiers</strong>, so the hyphenated form is usually correct.</span></p><div class="relative pb-6 w-full after:border-b after:border-stroke-300 after:w-full after:absolute after:mt-3"></div><h2 class="text-xl-medium [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5 pb-1">🌬️ Applying the rule to your example</h2><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">You asked specifically:</span></p><blockquote class="flex flex-col gap-3 border-s-2 border-foreground-300 ps-3" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">“If we have something like frost covered and frost‑covered which should we use?”</span></p></blockquote><h3 class="text-lg-strong pb-1 [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5"><strong>Correct choice: frost‑covered</strong></h3><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Because it is a compound adjective describing a noun (terrain, plains, hollows, etc.).</span></p><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">So your standardized entries become:</span></p><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>frost‑covered terrain</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>frost‑covered plains</strong></span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap"><strong>frost‑covered hollows</strong></span></p></li></ul><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">If you ever list it alone as a concept (rare), you could use “frost covered,” but that’s not how your dataset is structured.</span></p><div class="relative pb-6 w-full after:border-b after:border-stroke-300 after:w-full after:absolute after:mt-3"></div><h2 class="text-xl-medium [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5 pb-1">🌱 Summary of the Naming Rules</h2><h3 class="text-lg-strong pb-1 [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5"><strong>Pluralization</strong></h3><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Use <strong>plural</strong> for all countable features.</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Use singular only for inherently singular concepts.</span></p></li></ul><h3 class="text-lg-strong pb-1 [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5"><strong>Hyphenation</strong></h3><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Use <strong>hyphens</strong> for compound adjectives modifying nouns.</span></p></li><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Use <strong>spaces</strong> for simple noun phrases.</span></p></li></ul><h3 class="text-lg-strong pb-1 [&amp;:not(:first-child)]:pt-3.5"><strong>Consistency</strong></h3><ul class="relative list-outside marker:text-foreground-750 dark:marker:text-foreground-600 flex flex-col ms-4 px-1"><li class="ps-2" style="opacity: 1;"><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">Once a form is chosen (e.g., “snow‑covered”), use it everywhere.</span></p></li></ul><div class="relative pb-6 w-full after:border-b after:border-stroke-300 after:w-full after:absolute after:mt-3"></div><p><span class="font-ligatures-none whitespace-pre-wrap">If you want, I can help you apply these naming rules to your entire list so everything is uniform before you continue expanding it.</span></p></div></div><div class="mt-3"><div class="flex opacity-0 transition-opacity duration-300 ease-in-out items-center group-focus-within/ai-message-item:o